<h2>The weather in June 2018</h2>
<h3>Temperature deviations and extremes</h3>
<br><br>
Most of Europe was warmer than normal in June, like the two previous months. Only the south-western part of Iberia and northern Scandinavia as well as parts of European Russia were colder than normal. In northern Scandinavia this month was colder than May 2018, an event that is very rare. The warmth was accompanied by dryness in western, central and northern Europe. In these areas the cloud cover was also below normal and the sunshine duration above normal. At Shannon Airport (Ireland) it was the warmest June since 1946 and on the 28th the highest maximum temperature of 32.0 &#176;C was reported (its highest temperature since 1946). The mean temperature for Wales (UK) in June was +2.2 &#176;C above the long-term mean (1981-2010), making it the warmest June in a series from 1910, but in England the anomaly was only +1.8 &#176;C, the 4th warmest June. In Norway 15 meteorological stations reported new records for the monthly mean temperature and 8 stations new records of the daily maximum temperature in June. The absolute maximum temperature in Norway was 33.8 &#176;C on the 26th. In southern Sweden it was the hottest June since 100 years, at Lund even the hottest since 1889. Switzerland experienced the fourth warmest June since the start of their measurements in 1864.
